window.docContents[73].resolve({"/Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic/First-Proofs-in-Lean/#Formal-Software-Verification--Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic--First-Proofs-in-Lean--Classical-Reasoning":{"contents":"The rules used so far are constructive. Two principles of classical logic do not follow from them, the law of excluded middle and the elimination of double negation. Lean provides both in the Classical namespace.\n\n#check Classical.em\n\n\nClassical.em (p : Prop) : p ∨ ¬p\n\n\nClassical.byContradiction proves P from a proof that ¬P is impossible. With it, double negation elimination is one application away.\n\ntheorem not_not_elim (P : Prop) (h : ¬¬P) : P := by\n  apply Classical.byContradiction\n  intro hnP\n  exact h hnP\n\n\nThe first De Morgan law requires classical reasoning. A case analysis on Classical.em P decides which disjunct to prove.\n\ntheorem deMorgan_and (P Q : Prop) : ¬(P ∧ Q) → ¬P ∨ ¬Q := by\n  intro h\n  cases Classical.em P with\n  | inl hP => exact Or.inr (fun hQ => h ⟨hP, hQ⟩)\n  | inr hnP => exact Or.inl hnP\n\n\n","context":"Formal Software Verification\u0009Lecture 1: Motivation and Propositional Logic\u0009First Proofs in Lean","header":"1.5.5. Classical Reasoning","id":"/Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic/First-Proofs-in-Lean/#Formal-Software-Verification--Lecture-1___-Motivation-and-Propositional-Logic--First-Proofs-in-Lean--Classical-Reasoning"}});